Using Tailwind 4, how do I set the default font size for my theme?
# Setting Default Font Size in Tailwind CSS 4

In Tailwind CSS 4, you can set the default font size for your theme by customizing the `theme` section in your `tailwind.config.js` file. There are a few approaches depending on your specific needs.

## Basic Approach: Customize `fontSize` Default

```js
// tailwind.config.js
/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    fontSize: {
      // Override the base font size (16px by default)
      base: '18px',
      // Include other font sizes you need
      xs: '0.75rem',
      sm: '0.875rem',
      lg: '1.125rem',
      xl: '1.25rem',
      // ...etc
    },
  },
  // ...
}
```

## Advanced Approach: Configure with Typography Plugin

For more comprehensive typography control, consider using the `@tailwindcss/typography` plugin:

```js
// tailwind.config.js
/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      typography: {
        DEFAULT: {
          css: {
            fontSize: '18px',
            // You can also set other typography defaults here
            lineHeight: 1.6,
          },
        },
      },
    },
  },
  plugins: [
    require('@tailwindcss/typography'),
  ],
}
```

## Global CSS Approach

You can also set a document-wide font size in your global CSS:

```css
/* In your global CSS file (e.g., app.css or index.css) */
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

@layer base {
  html {
    font-size: 18px; /* Set base font size */
  }
}
```

## Setting Family-specific Sizes

If you want to set default sizes for specific font families:

```js
// tailwind.config.js
/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    fontFamily: {
      sans: ['Inter', 'sans-serif'],
      serif: ['Merriweather', 'serif'],
    },
    extend: {
      // Create font presets that combine family and size
      textStyles: {
        sans: { fontSize: '16px', fontFamily: 'Inter, sans-serif' },
        serif: { fontSize: '18px', fontFamily: 'Merriweather, serif' },
      }
    },
  },
  // ...
}
```

## Production Considerations

- Remember that changing the default font size affects responsive behavior - test thoroughly across devices
- Use relative units (rem/em) rather than pixels when possible for better accessibility
- Consider setting up a typography scale that maintains proper visual hierarchy
- Test your font settings with actual content to ensure readability on various devices

This configuration gives you a solid foundation for consistent typography throughout your application while maintaining Tailwind's utility-first approach.
Only, Tailwind 4 doesn't use a JS config file, it's all CSS
# Setting Default Font Size in Tailwind CSS 4

You're absolutely right, and I apologize for the confusion. Tailwind CSS 4 represents a significant shift in configuration approach, moving from JavaScript configuration to CSS-based configuration. Let me provide the correct approach:

## Setting Default Font Size in Tailwind CSS 4

In Tailwind CSS 4, you configure your theme directly in CSS using the `@theme` at-rule:

```css
/* In your main CSS file */
@theme {
  /* Set the default font size */
  font-size.base: 18px;

  /* You can also define your complete font size scale */
  font-size.xs: 0.75rem;
  font-size.sm: 0.875rem;
  font-size.lg: 1.125rem;
  font-size.xl: 1.25rem;
  /* ... other sizes */
}

@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

## Alternative Approach with CSS Variables

You can also use CSS variables to set your base font size in the `:root` element:

```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

@layer base {
  :root {
    font-size: 18px;
  }
}
```

## Using the Typography Plugin with Tailwind 4

If you're using the typography plugin, the configuration is now also in CSS:

```css
@theme {
  typography.DEFAULT.css.fontSize: 18px;
  typography.DEFAULT.css.lineHeight: 1.6;
}

@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

## Creating Font Presets

For more complex typography needs, you can define custom presets:

```css
@theme {
  /* Define font families */
  font-family.sans: ['Inter', 'sans-serif'];
  font-family.serif: ['Merriweather', 'serif'];
}

@layer components {
  .text-preset-sans {
    font-family: theme(font-family.sans);
    font-size: 16px;
  }

  .text-preset-serif {
    font-family: theme(font-family.serif);
    font-size: 18px;
  }
}
```

## Production Considerations

- The CSS-based configuration in Tailwind 4 provides a more intuitive way to manage typography
- You can still organize your theme settings into separate CSS files and import them
- Remember to check browser compatibility, especially when using newer CSS features
- Test your typography settings across various device sizes
- Consider how your base font size affects responsive design and accessibility

This CSS-based approach aligns with Tailwind 4's philosophy of bringing configuration closer to your actual stylesheets, making it more intuitive and easier to maintain.
